  <question type="stack">
    <name>
      <text>Performing reflection and maintaining symmetry in a  building facade</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>An architect is designing a building with a perfectly symmetric facade. The center of the building is aligned with the y-axis. The left side of the building contains a circular window at <b>W{@w_left@}</b> and a main entrance door at <b>D{@d_left@}</b></p>

[[jsxgraph width="400px" height="400px"]]
var board = JXG.JSXGraph.initBoard(divid, {boundingbox: [-7, 8, 7, -1], axis: true, showCopyright: false});

// Axis of Symmetry
board.create('line', [[0,0], [0,1]], {strokeColor: 'red', dash: 2, name: 'Symmetry Axis', withLabel: true});

// Left side features
board.create('point', [{#w_left[1]#}, {#w_left[2]#}], {name: 'Window (Left)', color: 'blue', size: 4});
board.create('point', [{#d_left[1]#}, {#d_left[2]#}], {name: 'Door (Left)', color: 'brown', size: 5, face: 'square'});
[[/jsxgraph]]


<ol>
    <li>To maintain symmetry, where should the corresponding window and door be placed on the right side of the building? <br>
       <p> Window (Right) = [[input:ans1]],</p><p> Door (Right) = [[input:ans2]]</p>[[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]
    </li>
    <li>In architectural terms, the two halves of the building are said to be identical. Does this mean the right half is congruent to the left half? <br>
    <p>    [[input:ans3]]</p>[[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]
    </li>
</ol>

<p><i>(Enter your answer in the form [x, y])</i></p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Worked Solution</p>

<b>Step 1: The Reflection Rule</b>
<p>Because the building is symmetric about the line \(x = 0\), every point on the left \((x, y)\) must have a corresponding point on the right \((-x, y)\).</p>
<ul>
    <li>Window (Left) {@w_left@} \(\to\) Window (Right) ({@-w_left[1]@}, {@w_left[2]@})</li>
    <li>Door (Left) {@d_left@} \(\to\) Door (Right) ({@-d_left[1]@}, {@d_left[2]@})</li>
</ul>

<b>Step 2: Congruence</b>
<p>Reflection is a rigid motion. In architecture, symmetry implies that the two halves are exact mirror images. Since the size of the windows, doors, and walls remain unchanged during a reflection, the two sides are congruent.</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
